{"title_page": "Seema Verma", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates | date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Use American English|date = December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Seema Verma\n|image       = Seema Verma official photo.jpg\n|office      = Administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = March 14, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Andy Slavitt]] (acting)\n|successor   =  \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|9|27}}\n|birth_place = [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Sanjay Mishra\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[University of Maryland, College Park]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[Johns Hopkins University]]<br />([[Master of Public Health|MPH]])\n|awards      = [[Sagamore of the Wabash]] (2016)<ref name=indy>{{cite web |last=Hakim-Shabazz |first=Abdul |title=Trump Picks HIP 2.0 Architect to Serve in Administration |url=http://indypolitics.org/2016/11/29/trump-picks-hip-2-0-architect-to-serve-in-administration |work=Indy Politics |date=November 29, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130043011/http://indypolitics.org/2016/11/29/trump-picks-hip-2-0-architect-to-serve-in-administration |archivedate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Seema Verma''' (born September 27, 1970)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/115/chrg/shrg30058/CHRG-115shrg30058.htm|title=- NOMINATION OF SEEMA VERMA, TO BE. ADMINISTRATOR, CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND MEDICAID SERVICES, DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES|website=[[congress.gov]]}}</ref> is an American [[health policy]] consultant and since March 2017 administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]], serving in the [[Trump Administration cabinet|Trump Administration]].<ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news |last1=Pradhan |first1=Rachana|title=Trump picks Seema Verma to head Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/donald-trump-administration/2016/11/seema-verma-to-head-centers-for-medicare-and-medicaid-services-231921|work=[[Politico]]|date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> She is the founder and previous CEO of SVC Inc., a health policy consulting firm, which was acquired by Health Management Associates (HMA) prior to her nomination to head CMS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/verma-sells-consulting-firm-following-cms-confirmation-1513300940-f19fdac9-aacc-4852-84c6-8f0153904053.html|title=Verma sells consulting firm following CMS confirmation|website=Axios}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nNot a MD, Verma received a bachelor's degree in [[life sciences]] from the [[University of Maryland, College Park]] in 1993. She earned a [[Master of Public Health]] with a concentration in [[health policy]] and [[healthcare management|management]] from the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health|Johns Hopkins School of Public Health]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|title=Donald Trump meets with Dr. [''sic''] Seema Verma, who may help in restructuring Obamacare|url=https://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2016/11/22/donald-trump-meets-with-dr-seema-verma-who-may-help-in-restructuring-obamacare419697/|work=The American Bazaar|date=November 22, 2016}}</ref> A graduate of the Richard G. Lugar Excellence in Public Service Series, she was selected for the [[American Enterprise Institute]] Leadership Network.<ref name=indy/>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nVerma served as vice president of planning for the Health & Hospital Corporation of Marion County<ref name=\"IndyStar\">{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=Seema Verma, powerful state health-care consultant, serves two bosses|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/08/25/powerful-state-healthcare-consultant-serves-two-bosses/14468683/|work=The Indianapolis Star|date=August 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6mOEGeheD?url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/08/25/powerful-state-healthcare-consultant-serves-two-bosses/14468683/|archivedate=November 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and worked at the [[Association of State and Territorial Health Officials]] in [[Washington, DC]].<ref name=\"Politico\"/>\n\n===SVC Inc.===\nVerma founded [[health policy]] consulting firm SVC Inc. in June 2001. She was president and CEO of the company, which has worked with state insurance agencies and public health agencies in preparation for the implementation of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]], and assisted Indiana and Kentucky, as well as other states, in the design of [[Medicaid expansion]] programs under the ACA.<ref name=\"Politico\"/> In her work with Indiana, Ohio, and Kentucky, she developed Medicaid reform programs under the [[Medicaid waiver|Section 1115 waiver]] process.<ref name=\"Newkirk\">Newkirk, Vann R., II (February 17, 2017). \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/02/seema-vermas-vision-for-medicaid/517077/ Seema Verma\u2019s Austere Vision for Medicaid]\". ''[[The Atlantic]]''. theatlantic.com. Retrieved March&nbsp;26, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"Glenza\">Glenza, Jessica (December&nbsp;4, 2016). \"[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/04/seema-verma-trump-centers-medicare-medicaid-cms Trump's pick for key health post known for punitive Medicaid plan]\". ''[[The Guardian]]''. theguardian.com. Retrieved March&nbsp;26, 2017.</ref>  Verma's firm provided technical assistance to the state of Michigan in the implementation of their 1115 Medicaid waiver, assisted Tennessee in their coverage expansion proposal, and supported Iowa's Medicaid transition to [[managed care]].<ref name=\"SVC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.svcinc.org/our-team.html?view=employee&id=1|title=Our Team: Seema Verma, MPH|publisher=SVC, Inc.|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}{{better source|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seema Verma official Transition portrait.jpg|thumb|Verma's Trump transition portrait]]\nIn 2014, concerns were raised over a potential [[conflict of interest]] arising from Verma's dual roles as both a health care consultant for Indiana and an employee of a [[Hewlett-Packard]] division that is among Indiana's largest [[Medicaid]] vendors.<ref name=\"IndyStar\" /> {{As of|2014}}, SVC Inc. had been awarded over $3.5&nbsp;million in Indiana state contracts while Verma was concurrently employed with Hewlett-Packard, earning over one million dollars during a period when the company had secured five hundred million dollars in state contracts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=5 loopholes in Indiana\u2019s ethics laws |url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/12/12/loopholes-indianas-ethics-laws/20308281/|work=The Indianapolis Star |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49668784683).jpg|thumb|President Trump and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media on March 16, 2020]]\nOn November 29, 2016, President-elect [[Donald Trump]] nominated Verma to serve as administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]], the agency that oversees [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], Medicaid, and the [[Health insurance marketplace|insurance markets]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanger-Katz |first1=Margot |title=A Trump Pick, and Why Indiana\u2019s Strict Medicaid Rules Could Spread |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/upshot/a-trump-pick-and-why-indianas-strict-medicaid-rules-could-spread.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 1, 2016}}</ref> On March 13, 2017, the [[United States Senate]] confirmed her nomination in a 55\u201343 vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2017/s86|title=On the Nomination PN49: Seema Verma, of Indiana, to be Administrator of the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services|work=[[GovTrack]]|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> One of her first actions was to send a letter to the nation's governors, urging them to impose [[insurance premium]]s for Medicaid, charge Medicaid recipients for [[emergency room]] visits, and encourage recipients to obtain employment or job training.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/on-first-day-in-office-new-medicaid-chief-urges-states-to-charge-premiums-prod-recipients-to-get-jobs/2017/03/15/8d36c480-0928-11e7-a15f-a58d4a988474_story.html |title=On first day in office, new Medicaid chief urges states to charge premiums, prod recipients to get jobs |first=Amy |last=Goldstein |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, 2018, Verma gave a speech<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=|first=|title=MEDICARE AND MEDICAID ADMINISTRATOR SEEMA VERMA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9uKSZKKHWeY|volume=|pages=|publication-date=July 25, 2018|publisher=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> in San Francisco in which she criticized proposals for \"[[Medicare For All|Medicare for all]]\".  She claimed that single-payer healthcare would \"destroy\" Medicare, which provides insurance for elderly people, and lead to \"Medicare for None\".<ref name=\":5\" />  The speech and her repeated attacks on medicare-for-all proposals led to a lawsuit alleging that her actions violated the [[Hatch Act of 1939|Hatch Act]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citizensforethics.org/press-release/crew-files-hatch-act-complaint-against-cms-administrator-seema-verma/|title=CREW Files Hatch Act Complaint Against CMS' Seema Verma|website=CREW|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn March 2019, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that in her role as CMS administrator, Verma approved communications subcontracts worth more than $2&nbsp;million of taxpayer funds on Republican-connected [[PR consultant|communications consultant]]s and other expenses to boost her visibility and public image. Included in the consultants' work were proposals to have Verma featured in magazines like ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and have her invited to prestigious events like the Kennedy honors to increase her public persona.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/03/29/seema-verma-contracts-1306652|title=Exclusive: Key Trump health official spends millions on GOP-connected consultants|date=March 29, 2019|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/20/contractor-glamour-magazine-profile-seema-verma-071727|title=Contractor proposed Glamour magazine profile for Medicaid chief|date=November 20, 2019|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n''Politico'' reported that Verma clashed with Acting HHS Secretary Alex Azar over which plans will replace Obamacare and who will get credit for those efforts, according to anonymous administration officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/26/hhs-trump-azar-verma-074149|title=Clashes among top HHS officials undermine Trump agenda|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>  Reportedly, this was not the first clash Verma had with her superiors as ''Politico'' reports that Verma hired a lawyer to file a claim of a \"hostile work environment\" against Secretary [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/10/seema-verma-tom-price-081059|title=Medicare chief sought to bring complaints against previous boss, as well|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2018, Verma filed a claim requesting that taxpayers reimburse her for jewelry that was allegedly stolen on a work-related trip to [[San Francisco]]. Although she requested $47,000, including a $325 claim for moisturizer and a $5,900 Ivanka Trump-brand pendant, she ultimately received $2,852.40 in reimbursement.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/07/medicare-chief-asked-taxpayers-to-cover-stolen-jewelry-077761|title=Medicare chief asked taxpayers to cover stolen jewelry|last=Diamond|first=Dan|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, columnist [[Michael Hiltzik]] of the ''Los Angeles Times'' declared \"Seema Verma is the greatest threat to public health programs in the Trump administration, with the possible exception only of Azar himself.\"  <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2019-12-12/verma-medicare-public-health|title=Medicare boss Seema Verma is a threat to public health|last=Hiltzik|first=Michael|website=LATIMES|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in Virginia, Verma moved several times across the United States with her family and once lived in Taiwan for five years before settling in the greater [[Indianapolis area]].<ref name=\"carmelmonthlymagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://carmelmonthlymagazine.com/seema-verma-carmel-resident-charge-american-healthcare/|title=Seema Verma: A Carmel Resident in Charge of American Healthcare |location= [[Carmel, Indiana]]|date=30 August 2017|work=Carmel Monthly Magazine|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> Verma's husband Sanjay is a [[child psychiatrist]] who runs a medical practice through the Indiana Health Group.<ref name=\"policymed1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.policymed.com/2017/02/senate-finance-committee-hearing-on-seema-verma-confirmation.html |title=Senate Finance Committee Hearing on Seema Verma Confirmation |work= Policy and Medicine |date=2017-02-27 |accessdate=2017-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"policymed1\"/> The couple has two children, Maya and Shaan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=Sara|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Seema Verma|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2017-03-15/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-seema-verma|accessdate=30 March 2017|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> Verma and her family currently live in [[Carmel, Indiana]].<ref name=\"carmelmonthlymagazine.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Seema Verma}}\n*[https://www.cms.gov/about-cms/leadership/ Biography at CMS.gov]\n*{{cite news|last1=Roob|first1=Mitchell|last2=Verma|first2=Seema|title=Indiana: Health Care Reform Amidst Colliding Values|url=http://healthaffairs.org/blog/2008/05/01/indiana-health-care-reform-amidst-colliding-values/|work=[[Health Affairs]]|date=May 1, 2008}}\n*{{cite AV media|people=Seema Verma |date=September 19, 2016 |year= |title=Why Indiana H.I.P. 2.0 Works & Obamacare Fails |medium=Radio broadcast |language= |url=http://www.wibc.com/blogs/garrison/segments-interviews/why-indiana-hip-20-works-obamacare-fails |access-date=November 29, 2016 |publisher=91.3 WIBC}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Slavitt]]<br/>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verma, Seema}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businesswomen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American health care chief executives]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Health and Human Services officials]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates | date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Use American English|date = December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Seema Verma\n|image       = Seema Verma official photo.jpg\n|office      = Administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = March 14, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Andy Slavitt]] (acting)\n|successor   =  \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|9|27}}\n|birth_place = [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Sanjay Mishra\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[University of Maryland, College Park]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[Johns Hopkins University]]<br />([[Master of Public Health|MPH]])\n|awards      = [[Sagamore of the Wabash]] (2016)<ref name=indy>{{cite web |last=Hakim-Shabazz |first=Abdul |title=Trump Picks HIP 2.0 Architect to Serve in Administration |url=http://indypolitics.org/2016/11/29/trump-picks-hip-2-0-architect-to-serve-in-administration |work=Indy Politics |date=November 29, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130043011/http://indypolitics.org/2016/11/29/trump-picks-hip-2-0-architect-to-serve-in-administration |archivedate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Seema Verma''' (born September 27, 1970)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/115/chrg/shrg30058/CHRG-115shrg30058.htm|title=- NOMINATION OF SEEMA VERMA, TO BE. ADMINISTRATOR, CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND MEDICAID SERVICES, DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES|website=[[congress.gov]]}}</ref> is an American [[health policy]] consultant and since March 2017 administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]], serving in the [[Trump Administration cabinet|Trump Administration]].<ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news |last1=Pradhan |first1=Rachana|title=Trump picks Seema Verma to head Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/donald-trump-administration/2016/11/seema-verma-to-head-centers-for-medicare-and-medicaid-services-231921|work=[[Politico]]|date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> She is the founder and previous CEO of SVC Inc., a health policy consulting firm, which was acquired by Health Management Associates (HMA) prior to her nomination to head CMS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/verma-sells-consulting-firm-following-cms-confirmation-1513300940-f19fdac9-aacc-4852-84c6-8f0153904053.html|title=Verma sells consulting firm following CMS confirmation|website=Axios}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAlthough she is not a MD, Verma received a bachelor's degree in [[life sciences]] from the [[University of Maryland, College Park]] in 1993. She earned a [[Master of Public Health]] with a concentration in [[health policy]] and [[healthcare management|management]] from the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health|Johns Hopkins School of Public Health]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|title=Donald Trump meets with Dr. [''sic''] Seema Verma, who may help in restructuring Obamacare|url=https://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2016/11/22/donald-trump-meets-with-dr-seema-verma-who-may-help-in-restructuring-obamacare419697/|work=The American Bazaar|date=November 22, 2016}}</ref> A graduate of the Richard G. Lugar Excellence in Public Service Series, she was selected for the [[American Enterprise Institute]] Leadership Network.<ref name=indy/>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nVerma served as vice president of planning for the Health & Hospital Corporation of Marion County<ref name=\"IndyStar\">{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=Seema Verma, powerful state health-care consultant, serves two bosses|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/08/25/powerful-state-healthcare-consultant-serves-two-bosses/14468683/|work=The Indianapolis Star|date=August 26, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6mOEGeheD?url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/08/25/powerful-state-healthcare-consultant-serves-two-bosses/14468683/|archivedate=November 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and worked at the [[Association of State and Territorial Health Officials]] in [[Washington, DC]].<ref name=\"Politico\"/>\n\n===SVC Inc.===\nVerma founded [[health policy]] consulting firm SVC Inc. in June 2001. She was president and CEO of the company, which has worked with state insurance agencies and public health agencies in preparation for the implementation of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]], and assisted Indiana and Kentucky, as well as other states, in the design of [[Medicaid expansion]] programs under the ACA.<ref name=\"Politico\"/> In her work with Indiana, Ohio, and Kentucky, she developed Medicaid reform programs under the [[Medicaid waiver|Section 1115 waiver]] process.<ref name=\"Newkirk\">Newkirk, Vann R., II (February 17, 2017). \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/02/seema-vermas-vision-for-medicaid/517077/ Seema Verma\u2019s Austere Vision for Medicaid]\". ''[[The Atlantic]]''. theatlantic.com. Retrieved March&nbsp;26, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"Glenza\">Glenza, Jessica (December&nbsp;4, 2016). \"[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/dec/04/seema-verma-trump-centers-medicare-medicaid-cms Trump's pick for key health post known for punitive Medicaid plan]\". ''[[The Guardian]]''. theguardian.com. Retrieved March&nbsp;26, 2017.</ref>  Verma's firm provided technical assistance to the state of Michigan in the implementation of their 1115 Medicaid waiver, assisted Tennessee in their coverage expansion proposal, and supported Iowa's Medicaid transition to [[managed care]].<ref name=\"SVC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.svcinc.org/our-team.html?view=employee&id=1|title=Our Team: Seema Verma, MPH|publisher=SVC, Inc.|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}{{better source|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seema Verma official Transition portrait.jpg|thumb|Verma's Trump transition portrait]]\nIn 2014, concerns were raised over a potential [[conflict of interest]] arising from Verma's dual roles as both a health care consultant for Indiana and an employee of a [[Hewlett-Packard]] division that is among Indiana's largest [[Medicaid]] vendors.<ref name=\"IndyStar\" /> {{As of|2014}}, SVC Inc. had been awarded over $3.5&nbsp;million in Indiana state contracts while Verma was concurrently employed with Hewlett-Packard, earning over one million dollars during a period when the company had secured five hundred million dollars in state contracts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Tony|title=5 loopholes in Indiana\u2019s ethics laws |url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/12/12/loopholes-indianas-ethics-laws/20308281/|work=The Indianapolis Star |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49668784683).jpg|thumb|President Trump and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media on March 16, 2020]]\nOn November 29, 2016, President-elect [[Donald Trump]] nominated Verma to serve as administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]], the agency that oversees [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], Medicaid, and the [[Health insurance marketplace|insurance markets]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanger-Katz |first1=Margot |title=A Trump Pick, and Why Indiana\u2019s Strict Medicaid Rules Could Spread |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/upshot/a-trump-pick-and-why-indianas-strict-medicaid-rules-could-spread.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 1, 2016}}</ref> On March 13, 2017, the [[United States Senate]] confirmed her nomination in a 55\u201343 vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/115-2017/s86|title=On the Nomination PN49: Seema Verma, of Indiana, to be Administrator of the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services|work=[[GovTrack]]|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> One of her first actions was to send a letter to the nation's governors, urging them to impose [[insurance premium]]s for Medicaid, charge Medicaid recipients for [[emergency room]] visits, and encourage recipients to obtain employment or job training.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/on-first-day-in-office-new-medicaid-chief-urges-states-to-charge-premiums-prod-recipients-to-get-jobs/2017/03/15/8d36c480-0928-11e7-a15f-a58d4a988474_story.html |title=On first day in office, new Medicaid chief urges states to charge premiums, prod recipients to get jobs |first=Amy |last=Goldstein |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, 2018, Verma gave a speech<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=|first=|title=MEDICARE AND MEDICAID ADMINISTRATOR SEEMA VERMA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9uKSZKKHWeY|volume=|pages=|publication-date=July 25, 2018|publisher=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> in San Francisco in which she criticized proposals for \"[[Medicare For All|Medicare for all]]\".  She claimed that single-payer healthcare would \"destroy\" Medicare, which provides insurance for elderly people, and lead to \"Medicare for None\".<ref name=\":5\" />  The speech and her repeated attacks on medicare-for-all proposals led to a lawsuit alleging that her actions violated the [[Hatch Act of 1939|Hatch Act]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citizensforethics.org/press-release/crew-files-hatch-act-complaint-against-cms-administrator-seema-verma/|title=CREW Files Hatch Act Complaint Against CMS' Seema Verma|website=CREW|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn March 2019, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that in her role as CMS administrator, Verma approved communications subcontracts worth more than $2&nbsp;million of taxpayer funds on Republican-connected [[PR consultant|communications consultant]]s and other expenses to boost her visibility and public image. Included in the consultants' work were proposals to have Verma featured in magazines like ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and have her invited to prestigious events like the Kennedy honors to increase her public persona.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/03/29/seema-verma-contracts-1306652|title=Exclusive: Key Trump health official spends millions on GOP-connected consultants|date=March 29, 2019|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/20/contractor-glamour-magazine-profile-seema-verma-071727|title=Contractor proposed Glamour magazine profile for Medicaid chief|date=November 20, 2019|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n''Politico'' reported that Verma clashed with Acting HHS Secretary Alex Azar over which plans will replace Obamacare and who will get credit for those efforts, according to anonymous administration officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/26/hhs-trump-azar-verma-074149|title=Clashes among top HHS officials undermine Trump agenda|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>  Reportedly, this was not the first clash Verma had with her superiors as ''Politico'' reports that Verma hired a lawyer to file a claim of a \"hostile work environment\" against Secretary [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/10/seema-verma-tom-price-081059|title=Medicare chief sought to bring complaints against previous boss, as well|newspaper=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2018, Verma filed a claim requesting that taxpayers reimburse her for jewelry that was allegedly stolen on a work-related trip to [[San Francisco]]. Although she requested $47,000, including a $325 claim for moisturizer and a $5,900 Ivanka Trump-brand pendant, she ultimately received $2,852.40 in reimbursement.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/07/medicare-chief-asked-taxpayers-to-cover-stolen-jewelry-077761|title=Medicare chief asked taxpayers to cover stolen jewelry|last=Diamond|first=Dan|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, columnist [[Michael Hiltzik]] of the ''Los Angeles Times'' declared \"Seema Verma is the greatest threat to public health programs in the Trump administration, with the possible exception only of Azar himself.\"  <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2019-12-12/verma-medicare-public-health|title=Medicare boss Seema Verma is a threat to public health|last=Hiltzik|first=Michael|website=LATIMES|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in Virginia, Verma moved several times across the United States with her family and once lived in Taiwan for five years before settling in the greater [[Indianapolis area]].<ref name=\"carmelmonthlymagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://carmelmonthlymagazine.com/seema-verma-carmel-resident-charge-american-healthcare/|title=Seema Verma: A Carmel Resident in Charge of American Healthcare |location= [[Carmel, Indiana]]|date=30 August 2017|work=Carmel Monthly Magazine|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> Verma's husband Sanjay is a [[child psychiatrist]] who runs a medical practice through the Indiana Health Group.<ref name=\"policymed1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.policymed.com/2017/02/senate-finance-committee-hearing-on-seema-verma-confirmation.html |title=Senate Finance Committee Hearing on Seema Verma Confirmation |work= Policy and Medicine |date=2017-02-27 |accessdate=2017-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"policymed1\"/> The couple has two children, Maya and Shaan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=Sara|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Seema Verma|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2017-03-15/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-seema-verma|accessdate=30 March 2017|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> Verma and her family currently live in [[Carmel, Indiana]].<ref name=\"carmelmonthlymagazine.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Seema Verma}}\n*[https://www.cms.gov/about-cms/leadership/ Biography at CMS.gov]\n*{{cite news|last1=Roob|first1=Mitchell|last2=Verma|first2=Seema|title=Indiana: Health Care Reform Amidst Colliding Values|url=http://healthaffairs.org/blog/2008/05/01/indiana-health-care-reform-amidst-colliding-values/|work=[[Health Affairs]]|date=May 1, 2008}}\n*{{cite AV media|people=Seema Verma |date=September 19, 2016 |year= |title=Why Indiana H.I.P. 2.0 Works & Obamacare Fails |medium=Radio broadcast |language= |url=http://www.wibc.com/blogs/garrison/segments-interviews/why-indiana-hip-20-works-obamacare-fails |access-date=November 29, 2016 |publisher=91.3 WIBC}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Slavitt]]<br/>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verma, Seema}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businesswomen of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American health care chief executives]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American public health doctors]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Health and Human Services officials]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n", "name_user": "MundaneCocoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seema_Verma"}
